Right<br /># Down&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Down&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(a3)&nbsp; righty&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Down<br /></div><br />What would have helped me was a User Manual or *something* telling me what button on the 3DS or PC actually did what thing.  Not a single 3DS review (video or blog/web page) nor PC review disclosed this info; but at least the 3DS version displays on-screen what some of the buttons do, so I was able to sort of work it out from there.<br /><br />Also for Tepples I guess: in case you want to know what button names map to what physical button on this adapter:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent"># b0&nbsp; = Triangle<br /># b1&nbsp; = Circle<br /># b2&nbsp; = X<br /># b3&nbsp; = Square<br /># b4&nbsp; = L2<br /># b5&nbsp; = R2<br /># b6&nbsp; = L1<br /># b7&nbsp; = R1<br /># b8&nbsp; = Select<br /># b9&nbsp; = Start<br /># b10 = Left Analog Button<br /># b11 = Right Analog Button<br /># a0&nbsp; = D-Pad Left<br /># a1&nbsp; = D-Pad Up<br /># a2&nbsp; = D-Pad Right<br /># a3&nbsp; = D-Pad Down<br /></div><br />And the <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">h0</tt> through <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">h3</tt> (for &quot;POV Hats&quot;) work/map identically in functionality as long as the &quot;Analog&quot; mode of the PS2 controller is enabled (by pressing the &quot;Analog&quot; button).

		

